(and its time shifts). The samples included in the average can be an arbitr=
ary subset of all the samples in the signal (e.g., samples within a finite =
time window or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statist=
ics)" title=3D"Sampling (statistics)">sub-sampling</a><sup class=3D"noprint=
 Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel_words" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Avoid weasel words"><span title=3D"The material near this tag=
 possibly uses too vague attribution or weasel words. (May 2015)">which?</s=
pan></a></i>]</sup> of one of the signals). For a large number of samples, =
the average converges to the true cross-correlation.
</p>
